Flight from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn toward democracy, the market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke ties with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to secessionist movements supported actively by Russia, which sought to keep both countries within the "sphere of influence" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeepers" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly erupt into hot wars.
Not only did this not happen, but we can now speak of solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve breakthroughs towards market economy and democracy.
Thereby, the "Neighbourhood Policy" of the European Union has also contributed.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
A state on the verge of failure, Georgia has now turned towards the West.
The success of various "colour revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also sparked change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at rapprochement with the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova aimed at restoring the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems that was unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its most important exports were scrap metal and timber, but its economy was growing.
In northeast Estonia, where the predominantly Russian-speaking population had settled during the Soviet era, Russia supported a so-called "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
High taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its composure.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country reorient its economy towards the West.
Western Europe, in turn, did what it could to integrate the Baltic States – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time sought to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, ultimately making Estonia one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, and it joined the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported to the same extent by Western Europe.
Certainly.
The country has done its best to forget its bleak past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and eager to advance the nation.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a justice reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to defuse tensions regarding Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to hinder reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is likewise important.
Estonia has shown, both during its independence and most recently during the crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument, that it can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this could be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate grounds for hope that it will achieve real independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians have ever been?
The missing reformers are partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That Transnistria, an industrialized region whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population, which comprises the majority of Moldovans of Romanian origin, planned closer ties with Romania, seceded from Moldova, dealt the country's independence a severe blow at the outset.
A civil war ensued, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they remain to this day.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Government representatives from Moldova have undertaken four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to strive for a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin asked for help from the EU observation troop EUBAM, but an EU initiative required Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks up-to-date insights into the situation in Moldova.
In April, for example, the EU and the USA learned about a proposed peace agreement only through a leak in a report in Germany.
This would, it seems, benefit Russia, as Moldova is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity.
If Russia has stabbed the West in the back in this manner, this would be a disastrous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
